introduction.p:
In , we learned how to solve the system
			\begin{pmatrix}
			dx/dt \\ dy/dt
			\end{pmatrix}
			=
			\begin{pmatrix}
			a & b \\
			c & d 
			\end{pmatrix}
			\begin{pmatrix}
			x \\ y
			\end{pmatrix}
			=
			A
			\begin{pmatrix}
			x \\ y
			\end{pmatrix} 
		provided the system has distinct real eigenvalues. If A has distinct real eigenvalues \lambda and \mu with eigenvectors \mathbf u and \mathbf v, respectively, then the general solution of the system is 
			\mathbf x(t) = c_1 e^{\lambda t} \mathbf u + c_2 e^{\mu t} \mathbf v.
		Furthermore, we can use the general solution of such a system to find the straight-line solutions to the system. If c_2 = 0, then all solutions will lie along the line in the xy-plane that contains the vector \mathbf u. Similarly, if c_1 = 0, then all solutions will lie along the line in the xy-plane that contains the vector \mathbf v.

example.p:
For the system in , the unstable line of solutions is 
				{\mathbf x}_1(t) = c_1 e^{2t} 
				\begin{pmatrix}
				3 \\ 1
				\end{pmatrix}.
			Each solution tends away from the origin as t \to \infty. The stable line of solutions is given by
				{\mathbf x}_2(t) = c_2 e^{-2t}
				\begin{pmatrix}
				1 \\ - 1
				\end{pmatrix},
			and each solution on this line approaches the origin as t \to \infty. By the Principle of Superposition, the general solution to the system is
				{\mathbf x}(t) = c_1 e^{2t} 
				\begin{pmatrix}
				3 \\ 1
				\end{pmatrix}
				+
				c_2 e^{-2t}
				\begin{pmatrix}
				1 \\ - 1
				\end{pmatrix}.
			If c_1 \neq 0, we have {\mathbf x}(t) \to {\mathbf x}_1(t) as t \to \infty. If c_2 \neq 0, we have {\mathbf x}(t) \to {\mathbf x}_2(t) as t \to -\infty. Thus, we have the phase portrait in .

subsection.p:
Suppose \lambda_1 \lt \lambda_2 \lt  0 and consider the diagonal system 
			\begin{pmatrix}
			x'(t) \\ y'(t)
			\end{pmatrix}
			=
			\begin{pmatrix}
			\lambda_1 & 0 \\
			0 & \lambda_2
			\end{pmatrix}
			\begin{pmatrix}
			x(t) \\ y(t)
			\end{pmatrix}.
		The general solution of this system is
			{\mathbf x}(t) 
			=
			c_1 e^{\lambda_1 t} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}
			+
			c_2 e^{\lambda_2 t} \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix},
		but unlike the case of the saddle, all solutions tend towards the origin as t \to \infty. To see how they solutions approach the origin, we will compute  dy/dx for c_2 \neq 0.  If

				x(t) & = c_1 e^{\lambda_1 t}
				y(t) & = c_2 e^{\lambda_2 t},

		then
			\frac{dy}{dx}
			=
			\frac{y'(t)}{x'(t)}
			=
			\frac{\lambda_2 c_2 e^{\lambda_2 t}}{\lambda_1c_1 e^{\lambda_1 t}}
			=
			\frac{\lambda_2 c_2}{\lambda_1c_1 } e^{(\lambda_2 - \lambda_1) t}.
		Since \lambda_2 - \lambda_1 \gt 0, the derivative, dy/dx, must approach \pm \infty, provided c_2 \neq 0. Therefore, the solutions tend towards the origin tangentially to the y-axis (). We say that the equilibrium point for this system is a sink.

example.p:
Consider the system
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x'(t) \\ y'(t)
				\end{pmatrix}
				=
				\begin{pmatrix}
				-5 \amp -2 \\
				-1 \amp -4
				\end{pmatrix}
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x(t) \\ y(t)
				\end{pmatrix}.
			The eigenvalues of this system are \lambda_1 = -6 and \lambda_2 = -3 with eigenvectors \mathbf v_1 = (2,1 ) and \mathbf v_2 = (1, -1), respectively.  Since the dominant eigenvalue is \lambda_2 = -6, solutions tend towards the straightline solution containing the vector \mathbf v_2 = (1, -1) more quickly ().

Consider the system
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x'(t) \\ y'(t)
				\end{pmatrix}
				=
				\begin{pmatrix}
				-5 \amp -2 \\
				-1 \amp -4
				\end{pmatrix}
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x(t) \\ y(t)
				\end{pmatrix}.
			The eigenvalues of this system are \lambda_1 = 5 and \lambda_2 = 1 with eigenvectors \mathbf v_1 = (3, -4) and \mathbf v_2 = (1, 1), respectively. Since the dominant eigenvalue is \lambda_1 = 5, solutions are closer to  the straightline solution containing the vector \mathbf v_2 = (3, -4) more as t \to \infty ().

ul.li:
Given a system of linear differential equations
				\begin{pmatrix}
				dx/dt \\ dy/dt
				\end{pmatrix}
				=
				\begin{pmatrix}
				a & b \\
				c & d 
				\end{pmatrix}
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x \\ y
				\end{pmatrix}
				=
				A
				\begin{pmatrix}
				x \\ y
				\end{pmatrix}, 
			we can use the eigenvalues of A to find and classify the solutions of the system.
